{{Expand French|Area di Sant'Omobono|date=April 2018}}
[[File:Ripa - area sacra di s Omobono 00915-6.JPG|thumb|290px|Area sacra di Sant'Omobono]] The '''Sant'Omobono Area''' (Italian: ''Area di Sant'Omobono'') is an archaeological site in [[Rome]] next to the church of [[Sant'Omobono]], at the junction of via L. Petroselli and il Vico Jugario at the foot of the [[Campidoglio]]. It was discovered in 1937 and contains much important evidence for [[ancient Rome|archaic]] and [[Roman republic|republican Rome]]. It contains altars and the sites of the temple of [[Fortuna]] and the temple of [[Mater Matuta]].
The temples and their sanctuaries lie between the [[Forum Holitorium]] and the [[Forum Boarium]].<ref name="Holloway2014">{{cite book|author=Ross R. Holloway|title=The Archaeology of Early Rome and Latium|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W6qOAwAAQBAJ&pg=PR11|date=12 May 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-76160-0|pages=11–}}</ref> {{As of|2012}}, the archaeological site is under re-investigation by a joint team from the Sovraintendenza ai Beni Culturali of the Comune di Roma, the Università della Calabria, and the University of Michigan.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Terrenato | first1 = N. | display-authors = 1 | last2 = et al | year = 2012 | title = 'The S. Omobono Sanctuary in Rome: Assessing eighty years of fieldwork and exploring perspectives for the future' | doi = 10.11141/ia.31.1 | doi-access=free | journal = Internet Archaeology | volume = 31 | issue = | page = }}</ref>
The site of Sant'Omobono is crucial for understanding the related processes of monumentalization, [[urbanization]], and state formation in Rome in the late Archaic period. The Sant'Omobono temple site dates to 7th&ndash;6th&nbsp;century&nbsp;[[BCE]], making this pair the oldest known temple remains in Rome.<ref>http://www.archaeology.org/issues/132-1405/trenches/1982-reexcavation-rome-earliest-temple</ref>
