{{Redirect|Yervandashat}} {{Infobox ancient site | name = Yervandashat | native_name = Երվանդաշատ | alternate_name = | image = Old Yervandashat.jpg | alt = | caption = The heights on the right bank of [[Aras River]] are the site of ancient Yervandashat | map_type = Turkey | map_alt = | map_caption = | map_size = 275 | relief = | coordinates = {{coord|40|07|N|43|39|E|display=inline,title}} | location = 1 km east of the current village of [[Yervandashat, Armenia]], on the right bank of [[Aras River]] in modern-day [[Turkey]] | region = | type = | part_of = | length = | width = | area = | height = | builder = King [[Orontes IV]] of Armenia | material = | built = 210 BC | abandoned = 360 | epochs = <!-- actually displays as "Periods" --> | cultures = | dependency_of = | occupants = | event = | excavations = | archaeologists = | condition = | ownership = | management = | public_access = | website = | notes = }} '''Yervandashat''' ({{lang-hy|Երվանդաշատ}}), was an [[Armenia]]n city and one of the [[Historic capitals of Armenia|13 historic capitals of Armenia]]<ref> [[Cyrille Toumanoff]]. Studies in Christian Caucasian history. — Georgetown University Press, 1963. — С. 75.:"The capitals of Armenia were successively: Armavira or Armawir of the Orontids (Manandyan, O torgovle 37) until the transfer by Orones IV of his residence to Eruandasat (*Orontasata)"</ref>, serving as a capital city between 210 and 176 BC during the [[Orontid Dynasty|Orontid]] rule over Armenia and the beginning of their successors; the [[Artaxiad dynasty]].
==History== Yervandashat was built around 210 BC by the last Orontid king [[Orontes IV]] of Armenia. It was at a height on the right bank of [[Aras River]], in the '''Arsharunik''' canton of [[Ayrarat]] province of [[Kingdom of Armenia (antiquity)|Armenia Major]]. Its site is 1&nbsp;km east {{clarify|date=February 2015|reason=Isn't Turkey west of Armenia?}} of the modern Armenian village of [[Yervandashat, Armenia|Yervandashat]], in the current [[Turkey|Turkish]] [[Iğdır Province|Province of Iğdır]].{{fact|date=October 2016}}
According to [[Movses Khorenatsi]], Orontes founded Yervandashat to replace [[Armavir, Armenia|Armavir]] as his [[Historical capitals of Armenia|capital]] after Armavir had been left dry by a shift of the [[Arax River]].
Ancient Yervandashat was destroyed by the army of the [[Persia]]n King [[Shapur II]] in the 360s AD.<ref>[http://www.armenian-history.com/Capitals/Yervandashat_History_eng.htm Yervandashat]</ref>
The archaeological site has not been the subject of major research, but preliminarily, the fortifications and some remains of palaces have been uncovered.
